<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Kind of Loving (Bravo Sunday at 5 p.m.): Splendid early (1962) John 
Schlesinger film starring Alan Bates and June Ritchie as a luckless 
working-class couple. (2:00) 
</P>
<P>
The Sea of Grass (TNT Monday at 5 p.m.): The most unusual of the nine Spencer 
Tracy-Katharine Hepburn movies, in which Hepburn plays a fragile woman crushed 
by the dominating Tracy, a feudal New Mexico rancher. Elia Kazan directed. 
(2:40) 
</P>
<P>
The Rise and Fall of Legs Diamond (Channel 13 Tuesday at 1:30 a.m.): Budd 
Boetticher's terse, stylish gangster movie, with Ray Danton in the title role. 
(2:00) 
</P>
<P>
Sullivan's Travels (Channel 5 Wednesday at 1:30 a.m.): The classic Preston 
Sturges satire in which Joel McCrea plays a Hollywood director who poses as a 
bum to get a fresh perspective on life. (2:00) 
</P>
<P>
The Story of Esther Costello (Cinemax Thursday at 7 a.m.): One of Joan 
Crawford's best later films in which she plays a misguided rich American woman 
intent on helping a deaf and blind English girl. (2:00) 
</P>
</TEXT>
