<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEIGHING ESTROGEN REPLACEMENT, CANCER RISK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Could the cancer risk associated with hormone replacement therapy, as it is 
practiced presently, have something to do with the source of material from 
which these hormones are manufactured? The risk of cancer is but one adverse 
side effect experienced by women who ingest the popular estrogen compound 
available on the market. Other unpleasant symptoms are edema, the inability of 
the liver to metabolize lipids, headaches, rapid heartbeat, high blood pressure 
and nausea. 
</P>
<P>
Presently, estrogen properties are being extracted from the urine of pregnant 
mares. While this estrogen is somewhat close to human estrogen in structure, 
there are molecular differences great enough to be of concern. Why don't we put 
pressure on the pharmaceutical firms to come up with something more closely 
resembling human hormones? The smaller doses of the mare-produced hormone are 
not the answer. 
</P>
<P>
JENNIFER ROBERTS 
</P>
<P>
Marina del Rey 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
