<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRAVEL NEWS AND BRIEFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Flights out of China have been delayed for hours as Chinese authorities search 
foreign airliners for stowaways using an escape route that has allowed dozens 
of fugitive dissidents to flee, airline sources said. 
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, sources said searches of foreign aircraft by armed paramilitary 
police have delayed flights for hours, prompting complaints from the airlines 
as well as foreign businesses, which have had shipments held up at airports 
while the containers were inspected. 
</P>
<P>
The Chinese national airline, CAAC, which is responsible for air cargo, has 
promised foreign airlines that it will look into their complaints. 
</P>
<P>
 -- -- -- 
</P>
<P>
Mexico will build its first high-speed "bullet train," the government newspaper 
El Nacional has reported. 
</P>
<P>
The electric train, to run between Mexico City and Queretaro, is scheduled to 
begin service next April, according to Transportation Secretary Andres Caso 
Lombardo. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, new rail lines in the northern border state of Coahuila and the 
Gulf Coastal state of Veracruz are scheduled for completion this year, Caso 
Lombardo said. 
</P>
<P>
He said the possibility of adding a new route between Mexico City and the 
Veracruz ports of Tuxpan and Tampico also is being explored. 
</P>
<P>
 -- -- -- 
</P>
<P>
Weekly charter flights connecting the Caribbean resort of Cancun with Mexico 
City and Tijuana are now operating, according to Notimex, Mexico's government 
news service. 
</P>
<P>
Latur, a new Mexican airline with a dozen 165-passenger planes, will promote 
the charter flights through offices outside Mexico, Notimex said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
