<HEADLINE>
<P>
POSTMAN ADMITS DELIVERING COCAINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BALTIMORE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A letter carrier has pleaded guilty to drug charges after admitting that he 
took telephone orders at the post office and delivered cocaine to some 
customers along his route. 
</P>
<P>
Isaiah Millings, 33, pleaded guilty last week to six drug-related counts in 
exchange for a two-year prison sentence. 
</P>
<P>
Postal inspectors and police secretly filmed Millings as he sold cocaine while 
delivering mail and as he transported the drug on other occasions using his 
official Postal Service vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
Police and post inspectors also taped Millings taking cocaine orders over the 
telephone at the post office. 
</P>
<P>
Millings' supplier, Antonio F. Brown, 49, also pleaded guilty and was sentenced 
to 10 years in prison. Brown, a native of Panama who entered the United States 
illegally, has a long criminal record and was wanted by police in South 
Carolina for escape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
