<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOR SOME, 'PARENTHOOD' IS NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some comments on Nina J. Easton's July 30 article about the Ron Howard's film 
"Parenthood," which, according to the headline, "reflects the movies' latest 
discovery: kids and families." 
</P>
<P>
Brian Grazer, Howard's partner in Imagine Films, is quoted as saying: "Now 
being hip is being a responsible dad. . . . It's hip to have substance." 
</P>
<P>
Hip? He makes child rearing sound like the latest dance step. 
</P>
<P>
'Hip to have substance" now? Does that mean that a short time ago it was "hip 
to be superficial"? 
</P>
<P>
I hope that reading Grazer's remarks doesn't provoke a bunch of folks to rush 
out and become parents so they too can share in the "hip" experience. Just as 
bell-bottom pants and alligator-emblem shirts went speedily out, so might this 
latest craze. 
</P>
<P>
And when a child no longer serves a desire for hipness, what do you say to 
little Mary or Johnny? "Sorry, kid, but you're out of style"? 
</P>
<P>
LAUREL DEWEY 
</P>
<P>
Glendale 
</P>
</TEXT>
