<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFING: EVENTS IN THE NEWS THIS WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A pair of commercial developments proposed for Cook's Corner in the foothills 
east of Mission Viejo will be the subject of a staff presentation and public 
hearing Tuesday before the county Planning Commission. The two projects, 
totaling more than 105,000 square feet of commercial and office space, include 
a series of retail shops, a gas station and a mini-mart. One of the projects is 
targeted for the current site of the famed Cook's Corner tavern, but developers 
say the roadhouse would be incorporated in the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081389-0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 94753 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 13, 1989, Sunday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 2; Column 5; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
96 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFING: EVENTS IN THE NEWS THIS WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The County Board of Supervisors on Wednesday will decide whether to narrow the 
list of possible sites for a new landfill in northern Orange County to three. 
County officials have spent more than a year looking at more than half a dozen 
potential sites, and county staff is recommending that the choices be narrowed 
to three: Olinda-Alpha Canyon, Gypsum Canyon and West Fremont Canyon. If the 
recommendation is adopted, county officials will begin a new round of 
environmental impact reports on each of those sites with a selection of a new 
landfill sometime early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
